        <section id="cost-of-living" class="mt-12">
          <h2 class="section-heading">Cost of Living</h2>
          <p>
            Switzerland is one of the most expensive countries in the world. However, the high salaries generally more than compensate, and many workers maintain a higher savings rate than in neighboring countries.
          </p>
          <div class="overflow-x-auto my-6">
            <table>
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Expense</th>
                  <th>Zurich</th>
                  <th>Geneva</th>
                  <th>Basel</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td>1-Bed Apartment (City Center)</td>
                  <td>CHF 2,000–2,800/mo</td>
                  <td>CHF 1,800–2,600/mo</td>
                  <td>CHF 1,500–2,200/mo</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>1-Bed Apartment (Outside Center)</td>
                  <td>CHF 1,500–2,100/mo</td>
                  <td>CHF 1,400–2,000/mo</td>
                  <td>CHF 1,200–1,700/mo</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Monthly Transit Pass</td>
                  <td>CHF 87 (ZVV zone 110)</td>
                  <td>CHF 70 (Unireso)</td>
                  <td>CHF 78</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Groceries (Monthly)</td>
                  <td>CHF 500–800</td>
                  <td>CHF 500–800</td>
                  <td>CHF 450–700</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Dining Out (Mid-Range, 2 people)</td>
